<!-- END APPRAISAL FORM -->
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      I work the eastern corridor and understand what motivates buyers to choose Wynnum. The suburb draws two very different and equally committed buyer profiles. Families who have been looking across southeast Brisbane and have concluded that Wynnum's combination of space, lifestyle and relative value is a better fit than anything closer to the CBD. And downsizers who are leaving larger inner-city or suburban homes and have decided that bayside village living, with a train line to the city when they need it, is exactly the next chapter they want. Both groups are decisive when the right property appears, because they have usually spent considerable time researching before they arrive at an open home.
    </p>
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      The Wynnum train line connects to the CBD in approximately 25 to 30 minutes, and bus routes serve the suburb for commuters who prefer not to drive. The housing stock runs from pre-war homes and Queenslanders through to post-war brick and more recent townhouses and medium-density dwellings. Block sizes are generally generous relative to the price point, which is a consistent draw for buyers who have been priced out of comparable land in inner suburbs. Properties within walking distance of the Esplanade carry a clear lifestyle premium, and the internal streets north of the foreshore offer the most consistent owner-occupier character.
    </p>
    <div style="display:flex; gap:1.5rem; flex-wrap:wrap;">
